To determine whether any code in OS_CondVarBroadcast is dead (i.e., can be removed without affecting program behaviour) we must know whether the calls it makes — and the constants/types that drive control flow — have observable side effects. - OS_ObjectIdGetById: Direct callee that produces return_code and may have side effects (state changes, transactions); removing its call could change behaviour if it does anything beyond returning a value.
- OS_CondVarBroadcast_Impl: Direct callee invoked when OS_ObjectIdGetById succeeds; its effects determine whether the conditional call is necessary.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit: Called (per the static call graph) by OS_ObjectIdGetById; may perform initialization or register state that is observable outside the function.
- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex: Called by OS_ObjectIdGetById; may access/modify global object tables or perform bounds checks that affect behaviour.
- OS_ObjectIdConvertToken: Called by OS_ObjectIdGetById; converts/produces the token passed back — may affect program state or be required for correctness of later operations.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: Called by OS_ObjectIdGetById; may undo or finalize transactions and thus has observable side effects.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Called by OS_CondVarBroadcast_Impl; may read/modify global state based on the token and thus influences observable behaviour of the broadcast implementation.
- OS_SUCCESS: Return-code constant used in the conditional; needed to know which return values lead to the Impl call (control-flow sensitivity for dead-code reasoning).
- OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE, OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_CONDVAR: Constants passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById that determine its behavior (which object table/lookup and mode) — affect whether the call does anything relevant and whether removing it changes behaviour.
- OS_object_token_t: Type of token passed by address; needed to determine whether modifications to the token by called functions are observable elsewhere (side effects via out-parameter).
- osal_id_t: Type of the var_id parameter; needed to determine if value-passing has any non-trivial semantic (e.g., encoded fields) that affect lookups.
- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: These unit-test / instrumentation hooks appear in the static call graph for this function. If present in the compiled code they may introduce side effects (registration, handlers, or altered control flow) that are relevant to determining whether portions of the function are actually doing observable work or are removable.

In short, to decide if any executed operation in OS_CondVarBroadcast is dead you must inspect the implementations and semantics of the direct callees and the secondary functions they call, plus the constants and types that control the conditional path and potential side effects.
